Let [`x^{b}\cdot x^{c}=x^{[$p]}\text{,}`] where [`b`] and [`c`] are natural numbers. How many possibilities are there for [`b\text{?}`]

[_]{$answerb}{10}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Let [`x^{b}\cdot x^{c}=x^{[$p]}\text{.}`] Many possibilities exist for [`b`] and [`c\text{.}`] Since [`b`] and [`c`] must be natural numbers, let's start with [`b`] equal to [`1\text{.}`] Then [`c`] must equal [$p-1], because [`x^{1}\cdot x^{[$p-1]}=x^{[$p]}\text{.}`] Considering all of the possibilities for [`b\text{,}`] notice that [`b`] can equal [`1,2,3,\ldots,[$p-1]\text{.}`] Therefore, there are [$p-1] possibilities for [`b\text{.}`] Note that [`b`] can't equal [$p] because that would force [`c`] to be zero,which is not a natural number.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

